The major discharge from the high side compressors (hot gas) enters three roof-mounted condensers.  A portion of the hot gas is also used for defrosting and for operation of the pumper drums.
The condensed liquid is returned to the high pressure receiver where it is fed to the refrigeration equipment.  Various safety systems are part of the anhydrous ammonia refrigeration system.  These include pressure relief valves, engine room ventilation, and safety interlocks.
Pressure relief valves protect the compressor discharge, condensers, pumper drums, and suction accumulators from over pressurization.
Safety interlocks include high pressure and high temperature alarms and cut outs for the compressors as well as high level floats and sensors for the vessels.  The high pressure cut-outs for the compressors are set at 225 psig.  The system also includes a solenoid-operated liquid ("King") valve which is controlled and shut down from the Watkins accumulator controls.

The refrigeration system is a totally closed system.  Historically, releases of ammonia from industrial refrigeration systems most often occur from leaking valves, malfunctioning pressure relief devices, or inadvertent releases during repair activities.  While these incidents can impact employees, they seldom lead to a release of a reportable quantity or represent an off-site impact (i.e., beyond the property line).  Moreover, a release of ammonia that could affect the environment is unlikely for the following reasons:

* Many of the high pressure liquid lines are located in enclosed areas that could help to contain such a release, and the outside piping is elevated to promote dispersion;

* Industrial standards were followed for the manufacture and quality control of these lines;

* Ammonia is not corrosive in this service;

* Most of the lines are elevated to minimize potential damage from fork lifts;

